I"p<h1 id="the-case-for-refurbishment">The case for refurbishment</h1>

<p>Very often the options appraisals assessments don’t take into account a number of crucial factors:</p>

<ol>
  <li>The financial cost of decanting the estate including buy-out costs of leaseholders.</li>
  <li>The loss of rental income for the Council both in the short term and long term.</li>
  <li>The social cost of decants on the housing waiting list and temporary accommodation costs.</li>
  <li>The environmental cost of discarding thousands of tonnes of embodied carbon and generating thousands of tonnes of new uneccessary carbon emissions in the new-build construction.</li>
</ol>

<p><a href="https://heygateestate.files.wordpress.com/2012/12/eblastrehouseredevelope.jpg?w=300&amp;h=211">This case study</a> by Gensler architects shows how the refurbishment of the Heygate estate could have saved 40,000 tonnes of carbon emissions:</p>

<p><img src="https://heygateestate.files.wordpress.com/2012/12/eblastrehouseredevelope.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>A <a href="http://www.engineering.ucl.ac.uk/engineering-exchange/files/2014/10/Report-Refurbishment-Demolition-Social-Housing.pdf">further report</a> by University College London (UCL Engineeering Exchange) says that…</p>

<p><img src="/images/uclengineering.png" alt="" /></p>

<p>The Architects Journal is running a campaign to show how refurbishment is almost always better than redevelopment using a number of case studies as examples: <a href="https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/retrofirst">https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/retrofirst</a></p>

